				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathrm{EQE}=\frac{{I}_{\mathrm{SC}}}{{P}_{\mathrm{laser}}A}\times \frac{\mathrm{hc}}{\mathrm{e}\lambda }$$\end{document}where the short-circuit current is ISC, the power density of incident photons is Plaser, the effective area is A, the Planck’s constant is h, the speed of light is c, the electron charge is e and the wavelength of the light is λ. The extracted EQE of 84.3% at 532 nm represents the highest value achieved from lateral or sensitized 2D diode at zero bias voltage (VDS = 0 V) (Additional file 1: Table S1) [46]. Such strong enhancement could be attributed to high optical absorption and long electron-carrier carrier diffusion length in MAPbI3 perovskite [28, 47–50]. These excellent optoelectronic properties of the perovskite can ensure the photogenerated carriers in the MAPbI3 to reach the p–n junction in the monolayer WSe2 channel, where they are separated by the built-in potential and extracted to external circuit (Fig. 1b).

